<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Baccharis emoryi </i>is an evergreen shrub with oblanceolate to obovate leaves that have widely spaced lobes and shiny upper surfaces. Plants appear as if they were a blend of <i>Baccharis pilularis </i>and <i>B. salicifolia. </i>Plants have composite heads with cream-colored flowers throughout the year. Like other <i>Baccharis, </i>staminate and pistillate heads are found on different plants, and seeds have long, feathery, white bristles and are wind dispersed (Hickman 1993). Some floras consider this taxon a synonym of <i>Baccharis salicina </i>(UCB 2017).<br/>
<br/>
<i>Baccharis sergiloides </i>is a short-lived shrub that requires relatively high subsurface moisture. Environmental conditions overlap those of <i>Salix exigua</i>. Little literature exists on its ecology. As with <i>B. pilularis, </i>it sprouts following disturbance and does not attain great age. Shrubs produce abundant, wind-dispersed seeds with substantial pappus bristles. <br/>
<br/>
The alliance occurs as open stands to dense thickets. Stands are typically small and occupy intermittently to seasonally flooded stretches of desert canyon bottoms and streams, or borders of springs and seeps. Boulders and bedrock often break up the stands although the rooting substrate is typically relatively fine to gravelly sand (Evens 2000).  The two indicator species of the alliance were previously viewed as separate alliances in the 2009 version of this classification, but more recently have been combined because of overlapping characteristics. More sampling is needed, though, to determine association level variation of <i>Baccharis emoryi </i>stands. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
